,Recommended,296830,14683688,"Posted: 27 February, 2015",all,ZombieMesh,"Let me just say I recommend this game only at a reduced price, if that ever happens. That may change based on whether or not the developers actually fix the infinite amount of bugs the game has.It's basically a buggy, magical Hitman: Blood Money. You're put into a sandbox area and given tasks, but are allowed to do as you please for the most part. Some people you HAVE to kill, but others are just a bonus.This game is buggy beyond reason. If you combine your items together, save, and then reload, those items will be glitched and unusable most of the time. If you kill someone, save, then reload, there's a chance that they will spawn in alive and then magically die after a few seconds. I had a glitch where a guy who was suppose to be in a coma walked around for a few seconds before resuming his normal function. The AI sometimes gets stuck on silly objects, or will survive an acid attack despite being half-way corroded. Sometimes you'll get in trouble for being in an un-restricted area. AIs sometimes forget their patterns and refuse to behave normally. I've had issues where music would loop over other music, even during cutscenes, forcing you to quit the game.There are probably a lot more glitches and bugs that I haven't mentioned. I'm guessing the huge ammount of bugs was due to the devs wanting to release it on Friday the 13th, and thus had to rush.Despite these awful and frustrating issues, the game is still pretty fun. If you've played Hitman: Blood Money enough times that you could probably kill someone in real life, you'll like this game. I've played around 10 hours and am close to beating the game. I will say that atleast 3 or 4 of those hours was backtracking because a series of bugs ruined a mission, but still.Hopefully the devlopers will patch out a good majority of the bugs. If and when that happens, I fully reccomend this game at $20 for the amount of content you're getting, but as of now, I wouldn't pay more than $10-15."
